<b>Devil-Linux</b> is a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../212/18212.xml">
Linux distribution</link> for use as a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../748/25748.xml">
router</link>/<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../296/1362296.xml">
firewall</link> which boots and runs completely from <recording wordnetid="104063868" confidence="0.8">
<artifact wordnetid="100021939" confidence="0.8">
<instrumentality wordnetid="103575240" confidence="0.8">
<sound_recording wordnetid="104262678" confidence="0.8">
<memory_device wordnetid="103744840" confidence="0.8">
<device wordnetid="103183080" confidence="0.8">
<phonograph_record wordnetid="103924069" confidence="0.8">
<medium wordnetid="106254669" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../902/18959902.xml">
CD-ROM</link></medium>
</phonograph_record>
</device>
</memory_device>
</sound_recording>
</instrumentality>
</artifact>
</recording>
 which can be put on an older <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../137/18457137.xml">
PC</link> that would otherwise go to waste. This, combined with a hub or switch is a solution some <O wordnetid="106832680" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../297/6097297.xml">
Linux</link></O>
 users prefer instead of using a dedicated router.<p>

Devil-Linux does not provide a graphical interface, making it a very light-weight distribution. Nevertheless, it includes a wide range of services (E.g.: DNS, Web, FTP, SMTP, ...), tools (<system wordnetid="104377057" confidence="0.8">
<artifact wordnetid="100021939" confidence="0.8">
<instrumentality wordnetid="103575240" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../545/19545.xml">
MySQL</link></instrumentality>
</artifact>
</system>
, <software wordnetid="106566077" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../529/18529.xml">
Lynx</link></software>
, <physical_entity wordnetid="100001930" confidence="0.8">
<sycophant wordnetid="110684827" confidence="0.8">
<person wordnetid="100007846" confidence="0.8">
<follower wordnetid="110099375" confidence="0.8">
<client wordnetid="109985075" confidence="0.8">
<leader wordnetid="109623038" confidence="0.8">
<administrator wordnetid="109770949" confidence="0.8">
<flatterer wordnetid="110095869" confidence="0.8">
<causal_agent wordnetid="100007347" confidence="0.8">
<case wordnetid="109898892" confidence="0.8">
<head wordnetid="110162991" confidence="0.8">
<director wordnetid="110014939" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../033/371033.xml">
Wget</link></director>
</head>
</case>
</causal_agent>
</flatterer>
</administrator>
</leader>
</client>
</follower>
</person>
</sycophant>
</physical_entity>
, ...) and security utilities (<software wordnetid="106566077" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../492/858492.xml">
OpenVPN</link></software>
, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../935/1026935.xml">
Shorewall</link>, ...) ensuring a high level of flexibility. Saving the configuration to a (later write protected) floppy disk, the settings can be restored at boot. Without using writable media, Devil-Linux is extremely secure from outside attacks.</p>
<p>

Devil-Linux uses a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../813/193813.xml">
Linux from Scratch</link> (LFS) build system that allows the user to create customized versions of this distribution.</p>
<p>

It uses the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../519/882519.xml">
grsecurity</link> kernel-patch.</p>

